                            <comment id="51263" author="luke" created="Wed, 17 Feb 2010 01:42:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It seems that the problem is as follows:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. The browser has a cached version of the secure page from a previous login and submits a matching If-None-Match request header with its post-authentication request&lt;br/&gt;
2. The browser gets back the 304 response.&lt;br/&gt;
3. At that point (as far as I understand) it should apparently display the cached page, but instead&lt;br/&gt;
   a) Firefox re-requests the previous URL (/spring-security-login)&lt;br/&gt;
   b) Safari does nothing (displays a blank page)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure at the moment why that would be the case. In a real application, this shouldn&apos;t be an issue as secured pages should not be cached at the client side.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem doesn&apos;t occur if you put the ShallowEtagHeaderFilter before the Spring Security filter chain. That way the Etag value changes when the response redirects to the login page.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="51286" author="luke" created="Wed, 17 Feb 2010 10:44:18 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve noticed that Firefox doesn&apos;t send the If-None-Match header when it is requesting the original page after a redirect (subsequent to logging in). However the DefaultSavedRequest still returns the original header which was cached prior to forcing a login. This results in the 304 code being sent by the ShallowEtagHeaderFilter, and Firefox doesn&apos;t know what to do.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve modified DefaultSavedRequest to ignore this header, which fixes the problem. However secure pages should generally have appropriate headers (no-cache etc) set to prevent the browser caching them to begin with.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
